---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import BmiCalculator from '../components/BmiCalculator.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="BMI Calculator for Men — Male Body Mass Index Guide"
  description="Free BMI calculator for men. Learn healthy BMI ranges for adult males, how muscle mass skews BMI readings, waist circumference guidelines, and what BMI numbers actually mean for men."
>
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-6xl px-4 py-10 sm:px-6">

    <section class="mb-10 max-w-3xl">
      <p class="text-sm font-medium uppercase tracking-wider text-(--color-accent-deep)">
        For Men
      </p>
      <h1 class="font-display mt-2 text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-(--color-ink) sm:text-5xl">
        BMI Calculator for Men
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-4 text-lg leading-relaxed text-(--color-body)">
        Calculate your BMI instantly. Men who exercise or carry significant muscle mass often get
        misleading readings — here's what your number actually means.
      </p>
    </section>

    <div class="grid gap-10 lg:grid-cols-[1.15fr_0.85fr] lg:gap-12">
      <BmiCalculator />

      <aside class="space-y-6 text-sm leading-relaxed text-(--color-body) lg:sticky lg:top-24 lg:self-start">

        <div class="rounded-xl border border-(--color-hairline) bg-(--color-accent)/5 p-5">
          <h2 class="font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">BMI ranges for men (adults)</h2>
          <table class="mt-3 w-full text-left text-sm">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-(--color-hairline) text-(--color-mute)">
                <th class="py-2 pr-2">Category</th>
                <th class="py-2">BMI (kg/m²)</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="border-b border-(--color-hairline)/60"><td class="py-2">Underweight</td><td>&lt; 18.5</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-(--color-hairline)/60"><td class="py-2">Normal</td><td>18.5 – 24.9</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-(--color-hairline)/60"><td class="py-2">Overweight</td><td>25 – 29.9</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="py-2">Obese</td><td>≥ 30</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
          <p class="mt-3 text-xs text-(--color-mute)">Source: WHO. Thresholds are the same for men and women.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="rounded-xl border border-(--color-hairline) bg-(--color-canvas) p-5">
          <h2 class="font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">Average BMI for men by age (US)</h2>
          <table class="mt-2 w-full text-left text-xs">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-(--color-hairline) text-(--color-mute)">
                <th class="py-1.5 pr-2">Age group</th>
                <th class="py-1.5">Avg BMI</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="border-b border-(--color-hairline)/60"><td class="py-1.5">20–39</td><td>27.5</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-(--color-hairline)/60"><td class="py-1.5">40–59</td><td>29.2</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="py-1.5">60+</td><td>28.6</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
          <p class="text-xs text-(--color-mute) mt-2">Source: CDC NHANES. Average ≠ healthy.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="rounded-xl border border-(--color-hairline) bg-(--color-canvas) p-5">
          <h2 class="font-semibold text-(--color-ink) mb-2">Waist size risk thresholds (men)</h2>
          <ul class="space-y-1 text-xs text-(--color-body)">
            <li>✅ <strong>&lt; 94 cm (37 in)</strong> — low risk</li>
            <li>⚠️ <strong>94–102 cm (37–40 in)</strong> — increased risk</li>
            <li>🚨 <strong>&gt; 102 cm (40 in)</strong> — high risk</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="mt-2 text-xs text-(--color-mute)">Source: WHO / NHS guidelines.</p>
        </div>

        <p>
          <strong class="text-(--color-ink)">Medical disclaimer:</strong> This tool is not a substitute for
          professional medical advice. Always consult a qualified healthcare provider about your weight and health.
        </p>
      </aside>
    </div>

    <article class="prose-section mx-auto mt-16 max-w-3xl space-y-8 text-(--color-body)">

      <section>
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">
          What is a healthy BMI for men?
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-3">
          The WHO healthy range is <strong>18.5 to 24.9 kg/m²</strong> for all adults. At the same BMI,
          men typically carry 6–11% less body fat than women due to lower oestrogen levels and greater
          lean muscle mass. This means a male BMI of 25 generally represents less body fat than a female
          BMI of 25.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3">
          The CDC reports the average BMI for American men across all ages is around 28.6 — technically
          in the overweight range. This reflects population-wide trends rather than a healthy target.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">
          Why BMI overestimates fatness in muscular men
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-3">
          BMI only measures weight relative to height — it cannot distinguish between muscle and fat.
          One kilogram of muscle and one kilogram of fat weigh the same. A 180 cm man weighing 95 kg
          has a BMI of 29.3 (overweight) regardless of whether he is a powerlifter with 12% body fat
          or a sedentary person with 35% body fat.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3">
          Studies have found that up to 40% of men classified as "overweight" by BMI have healthy
          cardiometabolic profiles. Conversely, "normal-weight obesity" — a normal BMI with high body fat —
          occurs in roughly 30% of men with BMI under 25.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">
          Waist circumference: a better signal for men
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-3">
          For men, waist circumference is often a stronger predictor of metabolic disease than BMI alone.
          Fat stored around the abdomen (visceral fat) releases inflammatory markers and raises insulin
          resistance, blood pressure, and LDL cholesterol.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3">
          The WHO recommends measuring at the midpoint between the lowest rib and the top of the hip bone
          (iliac crest). A waist above <strong>102 cm (40 inches)</strong> for men is associated with
          substantially higher risk of type 2 diabetes, heart disease, and some cancers.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">
          BMI ranges for male athletes
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-3">
          Many elite athletes have BMI values in the 27–35 range. Rugby forwards, American football
          linemen, and bodybuilders routinely exceed BMI 30 while maintaining low body fat percentages.
          In these cases, DEXA scans, hydrostatic weighing, or skinfold measurements are far more
          meaningful tools than BMI.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3">
          For recreational athletes and gym-goers, the rule of thumb: if your waist is below 94 cm
          and you have visible fitness markers, your BMI reading is likely inflated by muscle.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">
          When BMI matters most for men
        </h2>
        <ul class="mt-3 list-disc pl-5 space-y-2">
          <li>When used alongside waist circumference and blood markers</li>
          <li>For tracking long-term weight trends (not a snapshot reading)</li>
          <li>When assessing insurance or surgical candidacy alongside other risk factors</li>
          <li>As a first-screen tool in primary care before more detailed assessment</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

    </article>

    <div class="mx-auto mt-16 max-w-3xl">
      <p class="mb-6 text-sm text-(--color-body)">
        <a href="/" class="text-(--color-link) hover:underline">← Main BMI calculator</a>
        &nbsp;·&nbsp;
        <a href="/bmi-calculator-for-women" class="text-(--color-link) hover:underline">BMI for women →</a>
      </p>
    </div>

  </div>
</BaseLayout>